03878nam a22005415i 9780822397540DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223975407 a10.1515/97808223975402doi  a(DE-B1597)554348  a(OCoLC)846475099  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3534.6.J3bN68 2013 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a781.6309522231 aNovak, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapanoise :bMusic at the Edge of Circulation /cDavid Novak. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b51 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSign, Storage, Transmission00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 Scenes of Liveness and Deadness -- t2 Sonic Maps of the Japanese Underground -- t3 Listening to Noise in Kansai -- t4 Genre Noise -- t5. FEEDBACK, SUBJECTIVITY, AND PERFORMANCE -- t6 Japanoise and Technoculture -- t7 The Future of Cassette Culture -- tEpilogue: A Strange History -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNoise, an underground music made through an amalgam of feedback, distortion, and electronic effects, first emerged as a genre in the 1980s, circulating on cassette tapes traded between fans in Japan, Europe, and North America. With its cultivated obscurity, ear-shattering sound, and over-the-top performances, Noise has captured the imagination of a small but passionate transnational audience.For its scattered listeners, Noise always seems to be new and to come from somewhere else: in North America, it was called "Japanoise." But does Noise really belong to Japan? Is it even music at all? And why has Noise become such a compelling metaphor for the complexities of globalization and participatory media at the turn of the millennium?In Japanoise, David Novak draws on more than a decade of research in Japan and the United States to trace the "cultural feedback" that generates and sustains Noise. He provides a rich ethnographic account of live performances, the circulation of recordings, and the lives and creative practices of musicians and listeners. He explores the technologies of Noise and the productive distortions of its networks. Capturing the textures of feedback-its sonic and cultural layers and vibrations-Novak describes musical circulation through sound and listening, recording and performance, international exchange, and the social interpretations of media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aNoise musiczJapanxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397540zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397540.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles